<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<TcPlcObject Version="1.1.0.1" ProductVersion="3.1.4026.18">
  <POU Name="PRG_CMMT_AS" Id="{bbd6a5c8-f8db-448d-b188-8add5d730760}" SpecialFunc="None">
    <Declaration><![CDATA[PROGRAM PRG_CMMT_AS
VAR
	
	stCMMT_In : ST_CMMT_DriveToPlc;
	stCMMT_Out : ST_CMMT_PlcToDrive;


    fbCMMTBrake : FB_CMMT_BrakeControl;

    // Command from HMI or service controls.
    bManualBrakeRelease : BOOL;

    // Recommended release interlocks.
    bServiceMode               : BOOL;
    bSafetyPermitsRelease      : BOOL;
    bAxisMechanicallySupported : BOOL;



END_VAR
]]></Declaration>
    <Implementation>
      <ST><![CDATA[(*


// EtherCAT DIP Switch Configuration
SW1    SW2    SW3
 0      1      0
OFF     ON    OFF



Beckhoff EtherCAT master
          │
          ▼
CMMT-AS [XF1 IN]
CMMT-AS [XF2 OUT]
          │
          ▼
Next EtherCAT slave

*)

(*
CMMT-AS — CiA 402 motion start behaviour

```
There is no separate universal "Start" PDO.

The function of Controlword bits 4...6 depends on the operating
mode selected with object 6060h "Modes of operation".

Always wait until object 6061h "Modes of operation display"
confirms the requested mode before issuing a motion command.

---------------------------------------------------------------
MODE 1 — PROFILE POSITION
---------------------------------------------------------------

6060h := 1

The CMMT generates the position trajectory internally.

Before starting:
  1. Write Target position 607Ah.
  2. Write Profile velocity 6081h.
  3. Write acceleration/deceleration, when required.
  4. Make sure Controlword bit 4 is FALSE.

Start positioning with a rising edge of Controlword bit 4:

    Bit 4: FALSE -> TRUE

Relevant Controlword bits:
  Bit 4 = New set-point / start positioning
  Bit 5 = Change set-point immediately
  Bit 6 = 0: absolute position
          1: relative position
  Bit 8 = Halt

Position-command handshake:
  1. Set bit 4.
  2. Wait for Statusword bit 12 = TRUE
     (set-point acknowledged).
  3. Clear Controlword bit 4.
  4. Wait for Statusword bit 12 = FALSE.
  5. Wait for Statusword bit 10 = TRUE
     (target reached).

Merely changing Target position 607Ah does not start a movement.
A new FALSE-to-TRUE transition of Controlword bit 4 is required
for every new positioning command.

---------------------------------------------------------------
MODE 3 — PROFILE VELOCITY / JOG
---------------------------------------------------------------

6060h := 3

There is no separate Start bit in Profile Velocity mode.

Movement is controlled directly by Target velocity 60FFh:

    Target velocity > 0  : move in positive direction
    Target velocity < 0  : move in negative direction
    Target velocity = 0  : decelerate to standstill

Therefore, jogging is active while a non-zero signed target
velocity is being commanded.

Controlword bit 8 may be used to request Halt.

Before changing from Profile Velocity to another mode:
  1. Command Target velocity := 0.
  2. Wait until actual velocity is approximately zero.
  3. Select the new mode in 6060h.
  4. Wait until 6061h confirms the new mode.

---------------------------------------------------------------
MODE 6 — HOMING
---------------------------------------------------------------

6060h := 6

The homing method, direction, speeds and acceleration are
configured in Festo Automation Suite or through parameters.

Start homing with a rising edge of Controlword bit 4:

    Bit 4: FALSE -> TRUE

Relevant Statusword bits:
  Bit 12 = Homing attained
  Bit 13 = Homing error

Keep the homing-start command active while homing is running,
then clear Controlword bit 4 after homing has completed or failed.

---------------------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT
---------------------------------------------------------------

Controlword bits 4...6 must never be interpreted without first
considering the active operating mode.

The same physical bit can have a different function in:
  Mode 1: Profile Position
  Mode 3: Profile Velocity
  Mode 6: Homing
  Mode 8: Cyclic Synchronous Position

Mode 8 must not be used for simple direct PLC positioning unless
the PLC continuously generates cyclic trajectory set-points.
```

*)







(*

Reading brake status The values of 2150:05 are: Value Meaning 0 Brake closed 1 Brake open 2 Brake opening 3 Brake closing

*)



(*
    =====================================================================
    CMMT-AS HOLDING BRAKE CONTROL
    =====================================================================

    EtherCAT / CoE objects used:

        60FE:01    Digital outputs
        60FE:02    Digital output mask
        2150:05    Holding brake 1 status

    Brake release command:

        60FE:01 bit 0 = 1
            Request the holding brake to release/open.

        60FE:01 bit 0 = 0
            Remove the holding-brake release request.

    Output control mask:

        60FE:02 bit 0 = 1
            The fieldbus/PLC controls bit 0 of 60FE:01.

        60FE:02 bit 0 = 0
            The fieldbus/PLC does not control this output bit.

    IMPORTANT:

    The command is called "Brake Release Request" because the PLC is
    requesting that the CMMT releases the brake. It is not direct proof
    that the mechanical brake is physically open.

    For a vertical axis, releasing the brake without motor torque or
    mechanical support can allow the load to fall.

    The manual brake-release command should normally be restricted to
    commissioning, maintenance or service operation.

    During normal automatic motion, the CMMT should normally coordinate:

        Motor torque enabled
        -> brake released
        -> movement allowed

    and:

        Movement stopped
        -> brake applied
        -> motor torque disabled
    =====================================================================
*)





(*
    Example for a vertical axis.

    The brake release is permitted only when:

        - The machine is in service mode.
        - The safety system permits the operation.
        - The vertical load is mechanically supported.

    Replace these conditions with the interlocks appropriate for your
    machine risk assessment.
*)
fbCMMTBrake(
    i_bEnableManualBrakeControl := bServiceMode,

    i_bManualBrakeRelease       := bManualBrakeRelease,

    i_bReleasePermitted         :=
        bSafetyPermitsRelease
        AND bAxisMechanicallySupported,

    // Object 2150:05 from the CMMT input PDO.
    i_udiBrakeStatusRaw         := stCMMT_In.udiBrake1Status,

    // Objects 60FE:01 and 60FE:02 in the CMMT output PDO.
    io_udiDigitalOutputs        := stCMMT_Out.udiDigitalOutputs,
    io_udiDigitalOutputsMask    := stCMMT_Out.udiDigitalOutputsMask
);]]></ST>
    </Implementation>
  </POU>
</TcPlcObject>